check_pathway <- function(gene_set_name, db = msigdb_pruned, filter_hist = TRUE) {
  gene_set <- db[[gene_set_name]]
  higherInOld <- higher_in_old %>% toupper %>% .[. %in% gene_set]
  higherInYoung <- higher_in_young %>% toupper %>% .[. %in% gene_set]
  if (filter_hist) {
    higherInOld <- higherInOld %>% .[!grepl("HIST", .)]
    higherInYoung <- higherInYoung %>% .[!grepl("HIST", .)]
  }
  y <- list(gene_set_name = gene_set_name, higherInOld = higherInOld, higherInYoung = higherInYoung, all= gene_set)
  names(y)[4] <- gene_set_name
  return(y)
}

check_pathway(higher_in_old_pathways$gene_set[1])[1:3]

0.14 Model

0.14.1 Overview

Sensense is regulated by rnf2, a critical component of PRC1. In old mice, senescent genes normally silenced by PRC1 are reactivated, and cause the cell to sensence. Indeed, these genes are typically associated with repressive marks across a wide variet of ENCODE cell lines.

However, pulse of DNMT3L causes these senescence genes to be re-silenced, and allows to cells to exit senenscence. Interestingly, this silencing is stable even in the abscence of DNMT3L.

0.14.2 Previous literature

  • Cdkn2a

Interestingly, PK^INK4a (Cdkn2a) is previously implicated as a master regulator of senescence (ref 19-22 within). In our data, it appears DNMT3L does not silence this gene, even though PRC1 is supposed to supress it (ref 26-28 within).

check_gene(gene = grep("Cdkn2a", gene_info$gene_name, value = T), diff = F)

  • Rb1 and p53

Supposedly, Rb1 and p53 are the two master regulators of senescence, as stated in this review

check_gene(gene = grep("Rb1$|Trp53$", gene_info$gene_name, value = T), diff = F)

Interesting, neither gene seem involved in the senescnece observed here. p53s notable target genes, Bax, Apaf, Mdm2, and p21 (aka Cdkn1a), seem to be changed in DNMT3L pulse, but not during young MEF

check_gene(gene = grep("Bax|Apaf|Mdm2|Cdkn1a|Serpine1", gene_info$gene_name, value = T), diff = F)

Rb1 seems to supress E2F target genes via Cdkn2a ref. Since Cdkn2a doesnt seem to be changed during DNMT3L induction, Rb1 is probably not involved. Interesting, because Cdkn2a is a PRC1 target ref, and I think PRC1 is involved for some reason Cdkn2a escapes

  • PRC1 is important for senescence

Becuase our study identified Rnf2 as a core regulator of our differentially expressed genes, and Rnf2 is a core member of PRC1 genecards.com

Bmi1 defecient MEFs senescence early by allowing Cdkn2a to activate ref. In our case, it seems expression of Bmi1 increases upon DNMT3L induction. In addition, Cbx7, and Mel18 (Pcgf2) knockdown leads to cellular arrest, the same as Bmi1. But the data doesnt show difference in expression, except maybe Cbx7 being upregulated.

Zfp277 is required for Bmi1 mediated senescence, such that Zfp277 knockout cant be rescued with Bmi1

check_gene(gene = grep("Rnf2$|Bmi|Cbx7|Pcgf2|Zfp277", gene_info$gene_name, value = T), diff = F)

Good paper about PRC1 and PRC2 (introduction section)

  • How does DNMT3L recruit PRC to senescence related genes?

Turns out H3K27me3 is required for PRC1 recruitment to this loci, and Ezh2/Suz12/Eed is responsible since PRC1 is recruited to sites of H3K27me3. Expression of Ezh2 is increased, but not statistically significant.

JMJD3 (aka Kdm6b) removes H3K27me3 and allows senescence to happen ref.

check_gene(gene = grep("Ezh2|Suz12|Eed", gene_info$gene_name, value = T), diff = F)

DNMT3L binds directly to Ezh2 and Suz12. ref. Apparently, DNMT3L kicks out other DNMTs and prevents methylation of the loci. should bisulfite sequence this to check. The paper also performed DNMT3L Chip-seq, so it should be possible to check.

As for HOX genes, looks like HOTAIR recruits PRC2 to the hox cluster ref. Furthermore, knocking out DNMT3Ls binding domain causes HOX genes to increase expression (in spermatogonia) ref. This explains why Hox is higher expressed in old, because its losing PRC2 repression.

Actually, looks like others cannot replicate the interaction between DNMT3L and EZH2 ref. Yes interaction in ESC, no interaction in sperm.

A good review to study how PRC complexes are recruited to genomeic regions ref.

Should take a look at PRC1 (rnf2) and PRC2 (suz12) binding regions ref) and DNMT3L binding regions ref. To look for overlap.

  • Interaction with H3K9me3

DNMT3L is known to interact with K9me3 ref needed via setDB1. PRC2 complex members weakly interacts with setDB1, but strongly with G9a (which does the same thing as setDB1) ref.

0.15 Analyze overlap between H3K27me3 and DNMT3L binding

0.15.1 Data description

  • mESC data
    • mESC DNMT3L data from http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/geo/query/acc.cgi?acc=GSE49178 (http://www.cell.com/cell/fulltext/S0092-8674(13)01087-8)

find_overlapping_promoters <- function(subject_peaks, query_promoters = refseq, minoverlap = 1) {
  suppressWarnings(subsetByOverlaps(subject = subject_peaks, query = query_promoters, minoverlap = minoverlap))
}

chipseq_bed_promoter_overlap <- lapply(chipseq_bed, function(x) find_overlapping_promoters(x) %>% .$gene_name %>% unique())

0.20.1 TSS profiles

matrix_to_profile <- function(matrix) {
  x <- matrix %>%
    mutate(group = ifelse(gene_name %in% higher_in_old, "Higher in Old",
                          ifelse(gene_name %in% higher_in_young, "Higher in young", "Other"))) %>%
    gather(key = pos, value = signal, -gene_name, -group) %>%
    group_by(group, pos) %>%
    summarize(signal = mean(signal)) %>%
    mutate(pos = gsub("V", "", pos) %>% as.numeric(),
           pos = seq(-5000, 5000, by=100)[pos-5])
}

x <- lapply(profile_matrix, function(x) matrix_to_profile(x))

names(x) <- names(profile_matrix) 
tss_profiles <- bind_rows(x, .id = "mark") %>%
  filter(!grepl("Input|MEF", mark))

tss_profiles %>%
  ggplot(aes(pos, signal, color = group, group = group)) +
  geom_line() +
  facet_wrap(~ mark, scales="free_y", ncol=2) +
  theme_bw() +
  xlab("Position from TSS") +
  ylab("Read count in 50bp bins (rpkm)\n") +
  # theme_bw() +
  theme(legend.position="top", legend.title=element_blank())
